player.seasonOutlook: Okonkwo was selected by the Titans in the fourth round of April's draft. He is fast (class-best 4.52 40-yard dash) and athletic (35.5-inch vert), though he's on the small side and may not have the size for a conventional TE role in the pros. He was busy as a pass-catcher during his final season at Maryland, soaking up a 14% target share and 52-447-5 receiving line. However, he wasn't a vertical option, posting a 4.5 aDOT (third lowest in the class) and 8.6 YPR (lowest), and dropped five balls. He figures to work as a fullback/H-Back in the pros and isn't a fantasy option in 2022.

Shakir was selected by Buffalo in the fifth round of April's draft. Shakir is one of the top "offensive weapons" entering the league, having soaked up 317 targets, 71 carries, 31 returns and five pass attempts during four seasons at Boise State. Shakir aligned all over the field (60% slot for his career) and was efficient, posting a 2.89 YPRR (fourth in this rookie class). He is undersized, but he tested well at the combine (4.43 40-yard dash, 4.21 short shuttle) and his explosiveness and versatility make him an intriguing prospect. He'll open his career as a depth receiver in Buffalo.

Slayton is entering his fourth NFL season in search of a rebound after falling victim to the Giants' offensive struggles in 2021. Slayton's career got off to a great start as a fifth-round rookie in 2019 (48-740-8 receiving line), but he slipped in the TD department to a 50-751-3 line in 2020 prior to last season's debacle. He has been utilized almost exclusively as a vertical target, ranking top 10 in average depth of route during all three seasons. Slayton, whose 45% catch rate was dead-last in 2021, figures to be no higher than fourth on New York's depth chart when everyone is healthy, but Kenny Golladay, Kadarius Toney and Sterling Shepard (recovering from a torn Achilles) all have durability concerns, so the 25-year-old could again find his way to significant snaps. He's worth considering only in very deep leagues.

Strong was selected by New England in the fourth round of April's draft. He is on the short list of players from the FCS who nabbed a combine invite. He has an average frame and produced three 1,000-yard rushing seasons in four years at South Dakota State, including a big leap to a 240-1673-18 rushing line in 2021. Strong is a work in progress in passing situations, never clearing 22 catches for 197 yards in a single collegiate season. He was a big winner at the combine, measuring in with a large wingspan and performing well in all drills, including a class-best 4.37 40-yard dash (114 speed score). He's a sleeper for a passing game role in his rookie season, but Damien Harris and Rhamondre Stevenson will handle most of the backfield touches.

Drake is back for his second season in Las Vegas. The 28-year-old was expected to play a fairly significant offensive role in 2021, but ended up with 93 touches in 12 games while working behind feature back Josh Jacobs. Even when Jacobs was sidelined during Weeks 2 and 3, Drake shared the backfield with Peyton Barber and was limited to 112 yards on 23 touches. The season was a big letdown for a player who had been a top-20 fantasy back each of the prior three seasons. Perhaps new coach Josh McDaniels will breathe life into Drake's fantasy value, but it's hard to imagine consistent production as long as Jacobs is dominating the snaps. Drake will compete with Ameer Abdullah and rookie Zamir White for work and is barely worth bench consideration.

Ford was selected by Cleveland in the fifth round of April's draft. He played sparingly at Alabama before transferring to Cincinnati and eventually taking over as lead back. He has a good size/speed profile and his overall collegiate efficiency was good, though it did drop off a bit in 2021. He got a ton of pre-contact help (3.3 YBC) and was below average after contact (2.9) and in eluded and broken tackle rates. Ford averaged a healthy 10.0 yards per target, but on a lowly 6% target share. The dip in efficiency is a concern, but Ford's build and skillset suggest there's potential. He's buried on the Cleveland depth chart, so he's only worth stashing in deep dynasty formats.

Ingram was selected by Arizona in the sixth round of April's draft. He spent three seasons at Texas and one at USC during his collegiate career. He played a relatively similar role all four years, maxing out at 156 carries in 2021 and 35 targets in 2019. His overall efficiency is fine, but he was at his best this past season, posting the seventh best YAC (3.6) and eighth-best evaded tackle rate (8.1). Ingram is big, showed well at the combine and is a capable rusher and receiver. The Arizona depth chart is far from set behind James Conner, so Ingram has a shot to carve out a small role as a rookie. He's worth a look in dynasty formats.
